  "explanation": [
    {
      "heading": "What is a Trie?",
      "body": "A Trie (or Prefix Tree) stores strings by sharing common prefixes.\n\nEach path from root to a marked node represents a complete word. Nodes with `*` mark word boundaries.",
      "appearsAtStep": 0
    },
    {
      "heading": "Prefix Sharing",
      "body": "\"apple\" and \"app\" share the path `a → p → p`. Only the suffix diverges.\n\nThis sharing makes Tries memory-efficient for large dictionaries with common prefixes — like all English words starting with \"pre\" or \"un\".",
      "appearsAtStep": 2,
      "callout": "A 50,000-word English dictionary uses far fewer nodes than 50,000 strings stored separately."
    },
    {
      "heading": "search() vs startsWith()",
      "body": "**search(word)**: traverse character by character. Return true only if you reach the end AND the last node has `isEnd = true`.\n\n**startsWith(prefix)**: same traversal, but return true as soon as the path exists — `isEnd` doesn't matter.\n\nBoth are O(m) where m = length of the query.",
      "appearsAtStep": 5
    },
    {
      "heading": "search('ap') → false, startsWith('ap') → true",
      "body": "The node `p` at depth 2 exists — so `startsWith('ap')` is true.\n\nBut `p` at depth 2 has `isEnd = false` — 'ap' was never inserted as a complete word. So `search('ap')` is false.",
      "appearsAtStep": 6
    }
  ],
